column2:
Hi, 

I am trying to configure cucumber report on the docker collector, but for some reason collector is not able to located cucumber.json or other required details. I tried every possible path, but still no luck. cucumber.js goes into "cucumber-html-reports/.cache/cucumber.json"

ERROR : 
WARNING: No Enabled Jobs found with artifacts pattern: '*.json'

Config

hygieia-jenkins-cucumber-test-collector:
  image: hygieia-jenkins-cucumber-test-collector:latest
  container_name: hygieia-jenkins-cucumber
  volumes:
  - ./logs:/hygieia/logs
  links:
  - mongodb:mongo
  - hygieia-api
  environment:
#Jenkins server (required) - Can provide multiple
  - JENKINS_MASTER=http://xx.xx.xx.xx
#If using username/token for api authentication (required for Cloudbees Jenkins Ops Center) see sample
#  - JENKINS_OP_CENTER=http://username:token@jenkins.company.com
#Another option: If using same username/password Jenkins auth - set username/apiKey to use HTTP Basic Auth (blank=no auth)
  - JENKINS_USERNAME=username
  - JENKINS_API_KEY=password
  - JENKINS_CRON=0 0/5 * * * *
#Determines if build console log is collected - defaults to false
  - JENKINS_SAVE_LOG=false
  - JENKINS_CUCUMBER_JSON_FILENAME='*.json'


please help 

cheers,
Shashi
column5: Cucumber Docker Report Failure
column11:
364468867 I was able to fix this,  so learning are 

1. Make sure the cucumber.json or report file is archived through Post-build action through 'Archive the artifacts'.
2. make sure cucumber.json is there in archive path 
3. if still does not reflect try tweaking into mongo, (sometime it behaves weird)  shzshi

373165511 @depwaswho94 @satishc1 - according to the [docs](https://bower.io/docs/api/#allow-root) there's no need to run bower as superuser since it is a user command. If running `bower install` gives you a permissions error then you are likely not the owner of the folder. Run `chown -R $USER:$USER Hygieia` or something similar to make yourself owner of the folder.  matthewbeasley

Hi Team,

    In our dashboard, unable to see data for Sonar Anaylsis (it shows only line count) but not showing any data for number of blocker/critical issues present. We are using latest code of Feb-2 (commit bc6914b8d5c9a729280aed41f353e43d84fcc5f5).

     Our sonarqube version is - 5.6. I read from the posts that current code is not supported with old versions - https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/1415. Is this true?
what should be the correct SonarQube version to use with latest code?. Also it will be good if we maintain compatible versions for each collectors. 

Thanks
~Rushikesh
column5: Sonar analysis is not showing any data
column11:
365341025 @mrdmanohar  - it should be compatible for older versions. check your sonar properties if you have configured below metrics.

sonar.metrics[0]=ncloc,line_coverage,violations,critical_violations,major_violations,blocker_violations,violations_density,sqale_index,test_success_density,test_failures,test_errors,tests,alert_status
 nireeshT

private static final String JOBS_URL_SUFFIX = "rest/api/latest/plan?expand=plans&max-result=2000"

column2:
Hi Team,

I want to know how to setup ldap connection in hygieia. 

Please help me if it possible as  i am not finding a proper answer.

Thanks
Ashissh
column5: Question for Hygieia
column11:
363321506 Add the following properties in your api/dashboard.properties file with appropraite values of your LDAP server.

auth.authenticationProviders=[Authentication types you would like to enable, defaults to STANDARD, ex: STANDARD,LDAP]
auth.ldapServerUrl=[LDAP Server URL, including port of your LDAP server]
auth.ldapUserDnPattern=[LDAP User Dn Pattern, where the username is replaced with '{0}']

--LDAP Server URL, including port of your LDAP server
auth.ldapServerUrl=[ldap://company.com:389]
 --If using standard LDAP
--LDAP User Dn Pattern, where the username is replaced with '{0}'
auth.ldapUserDnPattern=[uid={0},OU=Users,dc=your,dc=company,dc=com]

If you are using ActiveDirectory with LDAP add the following properties 

--If using ActiveDirectory
--This will be the domain part of your userPrincipalName
auth.adDomain=[company.com]
--This will be your root dn
auth.adRootDn=[dc=your,dc=company,dc=com]
-- This will be your active directory URL (required for AD)
auth.adUrl=[Need an example]

Hygieia Doc Reference link : https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/gh-pages/pages/hygieia/api/api.md

After adding the above properties just run the api jar again and you will get an option of LDAP on the UI with default STANDARD (local) login.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/16320111/35844291-c1f61380-0b32-11e8-82af-fd3f0ffb4398.png)
    ameetsvshah

column11:
362258373 For now the problem is fixed for me. I added a docker container that deals with all proxy traffic. So I configured the proxy in one place and now I do not have to worry about proxy issues on collector level

More info: https://hub.docker.com/r/fengzhou/transparent-proxy/

```
  # Proxy
  transparent-proxy:
    image: fengzhou/transparent-proxy
    privileged: true
    network_mode: "host"
    environment:
      #This is upstream proxy, should support "CONNECT" HTTP method (Usually it is http proxy for HTTPS).
      - HTTP_PROXY=<proxy>:<port>
      #This is optional value to by pass network address without go through upstream proxy.
      #- NO_PROXY=
      #This is optional value and it can be any open port. Default value is "3129".
      #- LISTEN_PORT=
      #This is optional value, and should be different with other mark value used in iptables. Default value is "5".
      #- IPTABLE_MASK=
      #This is optional value for ports that can be transparent to proxy. The default value is "80,443".
      - PROXY_PORTS=80,443,22
      #This is optional value to start DNS proxy to help advanced filter by DNS. Default value is "53". To disable it use "0".
      #- DNS_PORT=
      #This is optional value to use advanced proxy routing configuration file. Default value is disabled.
      #- PROXY_CONFIG_FILE=
``` pversteijnen

column2:
The goal of this PR is make it so that a user can run `mvn install docker:build; docker-compose up -d` and have a UI, api, and a dev db. Then the user can rename the `docker-compose.override.example.yml` to `docker-compose.override.yml`, set the environment vars for the collectors they want to run and have those come up too. The compose file also maps the port of the mongodb in order to allow you to run the api or the collectors on the host machine if you are developing them. The api port is also mapped for development of the UI. The hose names have been changed to be the set to the names of the services. Docker Compose allows you to reference other containers via service name. The db information has been changed to match the docs. 

Future plans/ thoughts: clean up the `properties-builder.sh` files. The env var names are far too long for most of them. Also the way it currently works disallows optional env vars i.e all env vars must be set or lines must be commented out of the `properties-builder.sh` file in order for the collectors or the api to start. I was thinking of doing something like this:
```
if [ -z $ENV_VAR ]
then
  echo "collector.property=$ENV_VAR" >> $PROP_FILE
fi
```
However, I couldn't get it to work in time. The `Dockerfile`s themselves need to be cleaned as well. The `MAINTAINER` tag is deprecated for example. I would also like to add all the potential environment overrides to the override file to work as a bit of a reference to what all can be achieved

column11: 359906331 @pversteijnen - this is something we are working on. In the meantime, just clone the repo, run `mvn clean install docker:build` and you'll have updated images locally. From there you can push them to your own registry. Currently using our Docker images for production deployments is not recommended. Again, this is something that we are currently working on so stay tuned for a PR on this within the next couple months. matthewbeasley

359554817 @binnyg 
I think the issue may be that you have never run the Github collector even once before configuring the widget. And so the in the database there is no entry for the collector, and so the UI is failing.

Please run the Github collector once. 
From the path location "collectors/scm/github/target" under your hygieia installation:
Run the command: 
"java -jar ./github-scm-collector-2.0.5-SNAPSHOT.jar --spring.config.name=github --spring.config.location=<path to application.properties file>"

Make sure you have the following properties in your application.properties file.
These should be self-explanatory for the most part.

dbpassword=<database password>

github.cron=0 0/5 * * * *

I am not sure if the APIs support programmatic configuration of the widgets via API calls. But please feel free to look at the code repository, at the path "api/src/main/java/com/capitalone/rest". All the rest controllers are in there. You could look into the relevant controller depending on the widget you want to configure, and see if the API supports the "create" operation or not.

If you are interested in contributing and adding this capability though, we do encourage that. You would need to fork the master branch and incorporate your changes, and create a PR for review after you have thoroughly tested your changes. Thanks ! subodhbattina

A slow GitLab server causes the Hygieia data collector to receive 'java.net.SocketTimeoutException' from the Spring socket logic.  This gets caught and rethrown as 'org.springframework.web.client.ResourceAccessException'.  This causes a stack trace in the collector.

Please find a TAR file attached with notes describing the problem in full as well as two patched source files and their originals plus two 'diff' views of the patch.

Here is the contents of those notes in full:
---
PATCH TO OVERCOME GITLAB SERVER REST API SOCKET READ TIMEOUT
============================================================

Trying to implement a GitLab data collector for this installation
of Hygieia had a rather interesting runtime problem.  The GitLab
the GitLab server could run quite slowly at time due to system
tuning problems.  Since a Gitlab server has a significant number
of processes running all the time, inter-process latency can be
signficant when other processing makes significant claims on
system resources such as memory and CPU time.  From a web browser,
the GitLab GUI would sometimes return an error 502 (bad gateway)
under these conditions.  From a REST API viewpoint, a socket read
timeout came back, generating the runtime exception
'java.net.SocketTimeoutException' event.  The Spring API translates
this into 'org.springframework.web.client.ResourceAccessException',
which may be caught by the invoking Java code at the point shown
below with a (++) marking.  The (---) marking shows the segment of
stack trace applicable to the patched code and creation and recovery
from the socket read timeout event:


2018-01-10 11:13:20,619 ERROR o.s.s.s.TaskUtils$LoggingErrorHandler -
  Unexpected error occurred in scheduled task.

org.springframework.web.client.ResourceAccessException:
 I/O error on GET request for
"http://gitlab.company.com:80/api/v3/projects
/root%2Ftest-GITDATA/repository/commits
/?ref_name=master&since=2017-12-27T11:13:00Z&per_page=100":

Read timed out; nested exception is java.net.SocketTimeoutException:

          .doExecute(RestTemplate.java:580)

           ~[spring-web-4.1.7.RELEASE.jar!/:4.1.7.RELEASE]
        ... 15 common frames omitted

The patch provided here performs two actions on two files in the source
directory 'collectors/scm/gitlab/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard
/collecteur' to patch the Hygieia 2.0.4 release branch:

(1)   DefaultGitlabGitClent.java:  Retry three times if this event
      arises as detected by catch(ResourceAccessException).  If
      detected, perform Thread.sleep() for RETRY_SLEEP_TIME_MS
      milliseconds between attempts.  If this Thread.sleep() is
      interrupted--which is most unlikely--a catch(InterruptedException)
      will retry the socket read without counting an additional retry.
      Once a valid socket read is detected or the retry count expires,
      continue with current processing.

(2)   GitlabGitCOllectorTask.java:  If no data is returned from the
      getCommits() method due to socket timeouts or simply no data to
      report, defer updating the Git 'repo' object with update times
      until that condition is known.  This way, if there is a problem
      with obtaining data during the initial attempt at data collector
      startup time, the 'firstRun' condition is preserved and the next
      scan cycle of the collector will request the larger amount from
      the 'firstRun' condtion.  If it is still not available, the next
      scan does the same thing until the GitLab server finally gives up
      and produces data.  This is likely to occur since system cacheing
      will make its memory and disk resources more quickly available
      on successive scans until finally data is returned, at least so I
      suggest and speculate. Once the 'firstRun' condition is satisfied,
      successive data collector scans will request incremental results
      per existing behavior.


RELATED DATA COLLECTOR ISSUES
=============================

It might be prudent for the other Git data collectors to investigate
whether or not this issue might affect them also.  If the GitHub
data collector were to be examined, an easy way to test it would be
to set both(?) the socket connect and read timeout down from 20,000ms
to 1ms.  This would guarantee the problem to exist.  I cannot
assume which one of the two timeouts is invoked but this would be an
easy test.  It SHOULD be the read operation, since the log message
said 'Read timed out'.  The 'java.next.SocketTimeoutException' would
most certainly occur on its first invocation.  If so, then this same
patch technique could be implemented to catch
'org.springframework.web.client.ResourceAccessException'.

All other Hygieia clients probably would stand an examination of their
read timeout conditions since the product is still quite new and usage
data from production conditions is not yet widely known.  I would
suggest that numerous other Hygieia data collector applications could
use the same scrutiny and possibly a similar approach to bolstering the
response of the application against socket read timeout conditions.


PATCH DATA AND REPORTS
======================

The following files are provided to describe and implement this patch:

notes.txt
---------
This text file.


gitlab-collector-raw.diff
-------------------------
Output of 'diff -r ORIG-src src' to show every change precisely,
including white space differences.


gitlab-collector-no-white-spc-diffs.diff
----------------------------------------
Output of 'diff -rbBw ORIG-src src' to show the same changes but
not include white space differences.


ORIG-src/2.0.4/collectors/scm/gitlab
/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard
/collecteur/DefaultGitlabGitClient.java
---------------------------------------
Source code file 'DefaultGitlabClient.java' directly from 2.0.4 release.


ORIG-src/2.0.4/collectors/scm/gitlab
/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard
/collecteur/GitlabGitCollectorTask.java
---------------------------------------
Source code file 'GitlabGitCollector.java' directly from 2.0.4 release.


src/2.0.4/collectors/scm/gitlab
/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard
/collecteur/DefaultGitlabGitClient.java
---------------------------------------
Source code file 'DefaultGitlabClient.java' as modified for this patch.


src/2.0.4/collectors/scm/gitlab
/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard
/collecteur/GitlabGitCollectorTask.java
---------------------------------------
Source code file 'GitlabGitCollector.java' as modified for this patch.


EOF

column2: The login page uses ng-show to hide / show the login forms for standard and ldap. This is problematic because both are loaded into the DOM. This is because ng-show loads the element into the DOM and then uses the condition provided to determine an elements visibility. If we use ng-if instead then the elements are only loaded into the DOM if the condition is met.

column5: How to Implement Single sign-on in Hygieia
column11:
401083379 Set these properties:

```
auth.authenticationProviders=LDAP,STANDARD

auth.adUrl=ldaps://<some-ldap-server>
auth.adDomain=<ldap-domain>
auth.adRootDn=<dc config>

#Needed to query ldap
auth.ldapBindUser=
auth.ldapBindPass=

#SSO properties
auth.userEid=[name of the header containing EID]
auth.userEmail=[name of the header containing user's email]
auth.userFirstName=[name of the header containing user's first name]
auth.userLastName=[name of the header containing user's last name]
auth.userMiddelInitials=[name of the header containing user's middle name]
auth.userDisplayName=[name of the header containing user's display name]
``` matthewbeasley

Thanks,

column2:
This solves issue [#1856](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/1856). In the current state no matter what you attempt to set API_HOST to, you always get 'hygieia-api' as the hostname. In addition 127.0.0.1 is the current default which is rather useless as the api will never be reachable at this address.

The solution: remove the two export statements because they interfere with a user's ability to set the api hostname using ENV vars. Also change '127.0.0.1' to 'hygieia-api' since that hostname will be provided for you if you are using container linking or networking.
column5: UI conf-builder.sh to have sensible default for API_HOST

354338960 Hi @DimsumPanda,
Could you please try again with all these properties below and let us know if it works for you? Thanks !

// PageSize - Expand contract this value depending on Jira implementation's
// default server timeout setting (You will likely receive a SocketTimeoutException)
pageSize=100
queryFolder=jiraapi-queries
storyQuery=story
epicQuery=epic

jiraProxyUrl=<Full Domain Name of the Proxy>
jiraProxyPort=<Proxy Port>

// For basic authentication, requires username:password as string in base64

jiraCredentials=<base64 credentials>

jiraIssueTypeNames=Story

//  In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for 'sprint' or 'timebox' details,
 which includes a list of information.  This field allows you to specify that data field for your instance of Jira. Note: You can retrieve your instance's sprint data field name via the following URI, and look for a package name com.atlassian.greenhopper.service.sprint.Sprint;
your custom field name describes the values in this field:  https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name] //

jiraSprintDataFieldName=customfield_10007

// In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for 'super story' or 'epic' back-end ID,
which includes a list of information.  This field allows you to specify that data field for your instance of Jira.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's epic ID field name via the following URI where your queried user story issue has a super issue (for example, epic) tied to it; your custom field name describes the epic value you expect to see, and is the only field that does this for a given issue:
 https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name] //

 jiraEpicIdFieldName=customfield_10003

// In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for 'story points'
 This field allows you to specify that data field for your instance
 of Jira.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's storypoints ID field name via the following URI where your queried user story issue has story points set on it; your custom field name describes the
story points value you expect to see: https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name //

 jiraStoryPointsFieldName=customfield_10004

// In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for 'team'. This field allows you to specify that data field for your instance of Jira.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's team ID field name via the following URI where your queried user story issue has team set on it; your custom field name describes the team value you expect to see: https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name] //

 // Set this to true if you use boards as team
 jiraBoardAsTeam=true

Thanks ! subodhbattina

I don't quite recall what I fixed, but the changes since I posted include:

column2: As suggested in the [docker-maven-plugin docs](https://github.com/spotify/docker-maven-plugin) we should use [this plugin instead](https://github.com/spotify/dockerfile-maven). Doing so would allow us to bind our docker image creation (and optionally an image push) to a default maven build phase. I think the only functionality we would be losing is the ability to generate Dockerfiles which the plugin warns against and it doesn't seem like we do that anyway.
column5: docker-maven-plugin -> dockerfile-maven

column2:
Currently the Github collector won't pick up your proxy settings when running in Docker. We should provide a way for users to specify their proxy. One simple way we could do this is to look for an environment variable (e.g. GITHUB_PROXY) and then [here](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/collectors/scm/github/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/collector/RestOperationsSupplier.java) we can look to see if that ENV is set and if so, do something like [this](http://roufid.com/proxy-in-spring-resttemplate/). In fact, the Jira collector already does [this](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/collectors/feature/jira/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/client/JiraRestClientSupplier.java).

Currently there is a decent workaround. Modify the [Dockerfile](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/collectors/scm/github/docker/Dockerfile) and add `-Dhttp.proxyHost=<proxyHost> -Dhttp.proxyPort=<proxyIP> -Dhttps.proxyHost=<proxyHost> -Dhttps.proxyPort=<proxyIP>`
The whole command might look like this `java -Dhttp.proxyHost=docker.for.mac.localhost -Dhttp.proxyPort=8099 -Dhttps.proxyHost=docker.for.mac.localhost -Dhttps.proxyPort=8099 -jar github-scm-collector-2.0.5-SNAPSHOT.jar --spring.config.location=hygieia-github-scm-collector.properties`
column5: Github Collector in Docker doesn't pick up proxy information

# If using ActiveDirectory

#auth.adDomain=[company.com]

# This will be your root dn
#auth.adRootDn=[dc=your,dc=company,dc=com]
# This will be your active directory URL (required for AD)
#auth.adUrl=[Need an example].

And then when running your API jar file, point it to your API properties file as below:
java -jar <file path to your api jar> --spring.config.location=<file path to your api properties file>.

Hi Team,

I want to setup Hygieia on my System using docker-compose. So, I want to pull latest images from docker public repository. But I found that latest/versioned images  are not available in docker public [repo](https://hub.docker.com/search/?isAutomated=0&isOfficial=0&page=1&pullCount=0&q=capitalone&starCount=0) (for example, [hygieia-ui](https://hub.docker.com/r/capitalone/hygieia-ui/tags/) image is pushed before 2 years). 
**Do you push latest images to docker public repo or any  other repo, when you released? So that, I can pull latest/versioned images from there.**
Otherwise, I have to setup Hygieia's code on my system and create docker images. In that case, I have to repeat this step whenever new released will be available.

Thanks,
column5: Pull latest docker images from docker public repository
column11: 348546395 Hey saxenadeepakkumar! Integrating a push of our latest images to Docker Hub into our release process is definitely something on our radar. As you correctly pointed out you currently need to pull the latest code from the repo in order to get the latest and greatest version of Hygieia. This will change sometime in the near future. Thank you for your feedback and do let us know if you have other issues with the docker set up. matthewbeasley

347966831 Help team... Naumansh
354357500 @Naumansh - in your jenkins collector properties file you need to specify the List index for your username and api key. So instead of `jenkins.usernames=Naumansh` and `jenkins.apiKeys=abceef` you need `jenkins.usernames[0]=Naumansh` and `jenkins.apiKeys[0]=abceef`. This allows you to have different usernames and api keys for each server. Basically the error log is telling you that it couldn't find credentials at the index that corresponds to your server. matthewbeasley

354363061 Hi @pasan96:
Following up on this issue:
After some research in my local environment what I noticed is:
In the mongo db, in the document "collector_items" there is a property called "description".
If that property has a non-empty value, you will most likely see the response coming back. On the other hand if the property is empty you will get an empty response.

If you manually enter any value into the "description" property in the database, you will see a response.
I am going to have to get back to you on how this value gets populated for different collector types in the database. Thanks ! subodhbattina
354363913 Its possible that at this point only the build collector has the logic to populate a "collector_item" record with a non-empty value for the "description" property, whereas other collectors don't do that and so don't have a response coming back. Thanks ! subodhbattina

column11:
347240922 Hey GPreksha! I have a couple questions:
Are you referring to /UI/src/components/themes/dash.less?
What gulp command are you using to serve the UI? matthewbeasley
347473362 Hey Matthew, i modified dash.css in \Hygieia\UI\dist\styles.
I am using "gulp serve" command for UI  GPreksha
347541639 Awesome. Gulp serve is the correct command. What "gulp serve" does is it takes the files in the UI/src directory, does some processing and then outputs those files to another directory 'dist'. So, if you modify the files in your dist folder they will be overridden the next time gulp runs the "themes" task. For more information take a look at the [gulpfile](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/UI/gulpfile.js) and look for the line that starts `gulp.task('themes', function() {`

tldr; If you want your changes to persist, only modify files in the src directory.

Please let me know if this solves your issue! matthewbeasley

column2: We have two Hygieia env deployed in our docker infra. This hardcoded value in conf-builder.sh prevents us from being able to provide different API_HOST env variable for the two deployment.
column5: API_HOST is hardcoded in Hygieia/UI/docker/conf-builder.sh
column11:
349397507 Hey ibnjay! I'm currently looking into this. Are you using legacy container linking? matthewbeasley
351561572 @matthewbeasley Sorry didn't see that i already had a response. No not using legacy linking. Basically We launch the stack using docker-compose. Both instance of hygeia use the same network to expose frontend URLs. Using secrets we can configure API_HOST env for both stack differently. But the conf-builder.sh hard codes the value instead of just using the env variable. I suggest adding a check ```if API_HOST != null then export API_HOST=hygieia-api ``` Same thing for port.  ibnjay

column2:
These changes are for a gamification dashboard that encourages competition between teams by comparing them based on a set of metrics.

**Configuring Hygieia for the Dashboard**
The administrator must make an API call to the new `/gamification/metrics` endpoint to initialize the metrics in the database. The endpoint is documented in Swagger. Once the metrics have been initialized, the administrator can toggle metrics and set the score ranges in the administration page.

**Configuring the Dashboard**
To populate the dashboard, the user creates a product dashboard with at least one team. Assuming the administrator has performed the configuration mentioned above, a gamification tab will appear at the top of the product dashboard page. 

**Accessing the Dashboard**
When the user clicks on the gamification tab at the top of their product dashboard, they will be presented with a bar graph and a table showing the scores for each team.

359273089 @matthewbeasley how to set region property for aws collector, I don't see any?
 yks0000
363135356 @yks0000 - there isn't a property for this as the aws collector isn't intended work across regions. It is intended to collect data for the region it is deployed. In order to collect data from a region other than us-east-1 simply deploy the collector in the region for which you would like to collect data. 347030067 I made fix to my local by changing code as follows i.e. connecting to specific region `.withRegion(Regions.US_WEST_2)` for ec2 and autoscaling.

File that needs change: https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/collectors/cloud/aws/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/collector/DefaultAWSCloudClient.java#L78

After below changes, Please go to `collectors/cloud/aws` and `mvn install` as specified in `http://www.capitalone.io/Hygieia/aws.html`

At `line number 78, and 83` I changed `ec2Client and autoScalingClient` as follows:

```
ec2Client = new AmazonEC2Client(new AWSCredentialsProviderChain(new ProfileCredentialsProvider(settings.getProfile()),
                new InstanceProfileCredentialsProvider())).withRegion(Regions.US_WEST_2);

autoScalingClient = new AmazonAutoScalingClient(new AWSCredentialsProviderChain(new ProfileCredentialsProvider(settings.getProfile()),
                new InstanceProfileCredentialsProvider())).withRegion(Regions.US_WEST_2);
```

Seems like you might need to add a property For eg: `aws.region=xxxx` and have it called here.
 yks0000

363135356 @yks0000 - there isn't a property for this as the aws collector isn't intended work across regions. It is intended to collect data for the region it is deployed. In order to collect data from a region other than us-east-1 simply deploy the collector in the region for which you would like to collect data. As this isn't an issue per se I'm going to close this, but please feel free to continue the discussion.  matthewbeasley

350532924 I found the solution for this problem .
I have changed view.js under UI/src/components/widgets/codeanalysis
Fix : 
function processCaResponse(response) 

ctrl.reportUrl = response.reportUrl;       - orig code 
ctrl.reportUrl = caData.url;                          - my fix

Now it's working fine lenalevy

feature.jiraBoardAsTeam=true

349140186 Hi @e-macias:
I see that @Sbrenthughes has already responded. 
If I may add: From what I understand, this issue that you are seeing is happening when the collector is trying to fetch Story Data.

The main properties needed to fetch Story data are: 
feature.jiraIssueTypeNames=Story,
feature.storyQuery=story,
feature.pageSize=100

In your case, the story information comes the api call such as this below:
https://my.jira.com/rest/api/latest/search?jql=updatedDate%3E%3D'2016-03-01+00:00'+AND+issueType+IN+('Story')+ORDER+BY+updated+ASC&expand=schema,names&fields=*all,-comment,-watches,-worklog,-votes,-reporter,-creator,-attachment&maxResults=100&startAt=0  

On the response JSON that you get back, there is sub object called "schema".
And it essentially defines the "type" for each custom field found on the issues.
And it looks like in your case that "type" information may be missing and hence causing the error. Thanks ! subodhbattina
349477895 @subodhbattina pretty much yes. I am not entirely sure about the "sub object called 'schema'" part of your comment. So I cannot say for sure that you are correct there, but you might be.  e-macias
349985053 So inside the JSON response, there is another section for "schema" which has type information, basically a type field in each of those entries inside the "schema" section. So basically that type field might be missing on the response JSON. Hope this helps. Let me know if I can go ahead close this issue. Thanks ! subodhbattina
350058736 @subodhbattina I think I may have found the "schema" object you were referring to:
`"schema":{"parent":{"type":"array","items":"issuelinks","system":"parent"},
and it goes on for a while..`

I reached out to Atlassian regarding the issue being thrown by their jira-rest-java-client, and they suggested I reach out to [Adaptavist](http://www.adaptavist.com/w/) (the creators of the jira-groovy plugin). I am still waiting to hear back from them, and I was going to close this ticket afterwards, however, as this does not seem to be an issue with Hygieia, we may close this issue. I will continue to post if a solution is found for reference. Thank you for your help thus far.  e-macias
350080742 @e-macias Sure, you are very welcome. Please do keep us updated on your findings. I'll go ahead and close this ticket. Thanks ! subodhbattina
342929049 The exception appears to be thrown from 
`com.atlassian.jira.rest.client.internal.json.IssueJsonParser.parseSchema(IssueJsonParser.java:344)`
and that line looks like this: 
`(line 343) JSONObject fieldDefinition = json.getJSONObject(fieldId);`
`(line 344) res.put(fieldId, fieldDefinition.getString("type"));`

The root json object contains in it this json `{"custom":"com.onresolve.jira.groovy.groovyrunner:scripted-field","customId":12813}`. The root json object itself is pretty large and there are many inner objects that contain the "type" key, however this one does not and not sure what this one represents. 

Any help would be much appreciated, thanks. e-macias
344722346 I am not able to recreate this issue but if you are not behind a proxy then could you comment out
`feature.jiraProxyUrl=
feature.jiraProxyPort=`

I would also suggest using actual custom field numbers not
`customfield_XXXXX`
 Sbrenthughes

I commented out both proxy fields, however the issue still remains. While trying to recreate, are you working with a json that does not have the "type" field, as mentioned in my second comment?   e-macias

column5: How to make the API work in the same network than  docker ?
column11:
361187191 I ran into this issue that the UI could not connect to the API. What worked for me was in the UI configuring set the API with my external IP address. Some how this solved my issue of not connecting to the API (using Docker-Compose)
```
  # Hygieia UI layer
  hygieia-ui:
    image: pversteijnen/hygieia-ui
    container_name: hygieia-ui
    environment:
      - jasypt.encryptor.password=hygieiasecret
      - API_HOST=<your external IP>
      - API_PORT=8080
    ports:
      - "8090:80"
    links:
      - hygieia-api
``` pversteijnen
363141718 @samyzemmouri - we have recently merged the first in a series of refactors revolving our docker setup. Please pull the latest code and retry this. If using compose, you should be able to access the api by just referencing https://api/ as compose will set up the hostname for you. Please let me know if you continue to experience issues or have feedback you would like to share.  matthewbeasley

column2:
I'm wondering if we need to chose _just one_ of the Jenkins collectors to use. We currently have a pull-based collector running, and we also have the Hygieia Jenkins Plugin on our Jenkins which is _pushing_ data to the Hygieia API.

_**Will having both collectors running at the same time cause problems with the data in mongo or with the widgets' interpretation of that data**_

If so, _**are there any features missing from the push-based collector that would make it incomplete to run on its own?**_ iow Does it matter which one you pick if you pick just one?

I'm mostly wondering if there are *known* issues when working with both. I've seen some issues when experimenting. 

One of the issues I have noticed is that Jenkins jobs will be _listed twice_ in the Jenkins widget, and you have to do some HTML inspection or trial-and-error to figure out which one you want.  

Also, there may have been some care needed when setting up the Product Dashboard, in that it needed to incorporate a Team Dashboard that was tracking a push vs. pull Jenkins collector, so that when it went and queried for commits, it was getting commits put into mongo by the right collector.
 
During demos, the pull collector also doesn't update very frequently if you're trying to demo the Product Dashboard's pipeline widget moving commits along.

FYI Some of the info about push/pull was gathered here: http://www.capitalone.io/Hygieia/hygieia-jenkins-plugin.html
Thanks.
column5: Question: Will using the Jenkins pull collector and push collector (plugin) together cause issues
column11: 401083804 @kwhickey - you can run one or the other or both. It doesn't matter.  matthewbeasley
